default(a)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe examining officer considering (or a senior officer being satisfied) that detention is 
defaultnecessary in order to assist in determiningdefault whether a person appears to be 
defaulta person falling within section 40(1)(b) [i.e. a 
defaultperson who is or has been concern
defaulted in the commission, preparation or instigation of acts of terrorism;]
default&#xa0;
default(b)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe examining officer considering (or a senior officer being satisfied) that there are 
defaultgrounds for suspectingdefault that the person appears to be 
defaulta person falling within section 40(1)(b); or
default&#xa0;
default(c)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe examining officer considering (or a senior officer being satisfied) that there are 
defaultreasonable grounds for suspectingdefault that the person appears to be a person falling within section 40(1)(b). 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default(a)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe first 
default(“
defaultnecessary in order to assist in 
defaultdetermining
default”) 
defaultis
default 
defaultlittle more than a statement of the obligation that rests upon any officer whose decision is liable to infringe the Article 8 (or Article 5) rights of another person.  It is based on the existing threshold for the taking of fingerprints or 
defaulta 
defaultDNA sample,
default 
defaultwhich the Government does not propose
default to amend, 
defaultand resembles the “
defaultnecessity
default” threshold that the Bill proposes to introduce for 
defaultauthorisation by the review officer of 
defaultcontinued 
defaultdetention after a so far unspecified period.
default&#xa0;
default(b)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe second (“
defaultgrounds for suspecting
default”)
default would echo the subjective belief standards already present in paragraphs 2(2)(b) and 2(4) of Schedule 7.  It would require the officer to have formed a suspicion
default, 
defaultwhether on the basis of information supplied by others, behavioural assessment or even just intuition
default.  It would however
default 
defaultensure that (in the words of Lord Bingham, in the conte
defaultxt of a stop and search power) a ports officer
default is not deterred from 
defaultdetaining 
default“
defaulta person whom he does suspect as a potential terrorist by the fear that he could not show reasonable grounds for his 
defaultsuspicion
default”.
default&#xa0;
default(c)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe third (“
defaultreasonable grounds for suspecting
default”)
default 
defaultis the default threshold for most stop and search powers, and 
defaultwas 
defaultthe solution favoured
default by the JCHR
default in relation to the detention power
default.
default  It is related to (though not identical to) the proposal in the Bill that strip searches should be conducted 
defaultonly where the examining officer has “
defaultreasonable grounds to suspect that the person is concealing something which may be evidence that the person falls within section 40(1)(b)
default”.
